Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER STRUCTURE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Minimal PHP lexer state expressed as a flat integer-keyed record threaded
through every helper: source pointer, byte position, 1-based line/column for
diagnostics, and the produced tokens list. Mirrors the committed Elixir lexer's
single-state-record discipline so Stage B can rely on identical accessor
semantics. A 40-byte allocation is exactly 5 fields x 8 bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 fields x 8 bytes) accessed via memory_get/set_int64 at
offsets 0/8/16/24/32 for source, position, line, column, tokens. tokens is
populated by tokenize_php once it creates the output list.
@End Implementation
Type called "PhpLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    position as Integer         Note: Current byte position
    line as Integer             Note: Current line number
    column as Integer           Note: Current column number
    tokens as Integer           Note: List of tokens
End Type

@Reasoning:
Per-token record carrying type tag, original textual lexeme, source position
for diagnostics, and an out-of-band value slot reserved for literals that carry
a parsed representation. Kept opaque at this layer; Stage A consumers use the
accessors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record laid out as token_type@0, lexeme@8, line@16, column@24,
value@32. Allocated by create_token; value initialized to 0.
@End Implementation
Type called "PhpToken":
    token_type as Integer       Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer           Note: Token text (owned copy via substring)
    line as Integer             Note: Line number
    column as Integer           Note: Column number
    value as Integer            Note: Parsed value slot
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The lexer is a 40-byte flat record holding (source ptr, position, line, column,
tokens). Position starts at 0 (string_char_at is 0-indexed); line and column
start at 1 to match editor/diagnostic conventions. tokens starts at 0 and is
filled by tokenize_php.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_php_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new PHP lexer

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0           Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1          Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1          Note: column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 0          Note: tokens

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level tokenisation loop. PHP source is HTML interleaved with PHP code
regions opened by '<?php'/'<?='/'<?' and closed by '?>'. Outside PHP we collect
inline HTML; inside PHP we skip whitespace/comments and emit code tokens. The
loop always advances at least one byte or emits a terminal EOF, guaranteeing
termination. EOF is appended so downstream parsing has a uniform terminal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "tokenize_php" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize entire PHP source

    Let tokens be proc list_create from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, tokens

    Note: in_php is 1 when inside a <?php ... ?> region, 0 in inline-HTML mode
    Let in_php be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Let eof_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF, ""
            proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, eof_tok
            Break
        End If

        If in_php is equal to 0:
            Note: Inline-HTML mode: scan until next open tag.
            Let open_pos be proc find_open_tag with lexer
            If open_pos is equal to 0:
                Note: No more open tags: rest of file is HTML.
                proc scan_inline_html_to_end with lexer
                Let eof_tok2 be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF, ""
                proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, eof_tok2
                Break
            Otherwise:
                proc scan_open_tag with lexer
                Set in_php to 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc skip_whitespace with lexer
            Let ch2 be proc peek_char with lexer
            If ch2 is equal to 0:
                Let eof_tok3 be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF, ""
                proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, eof_tok3
                Break
            End If

            Note: Close tag '?>' returns to HTML mode.
            If ch2 is equal to 63:                       Note: '?'
                Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
                If nx is equal to 62:                    Note: '>'
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    Let close_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_CLOSE_TAG, "?>"
                    proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, close_tok
                    Set in_php to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Let tok be proc next_token with lexer
                    proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, tok
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Let tok2 be proc next_token with lexer
                proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, tok2
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return tokens
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public one-shot lex driver matching the cross-frontend naming convention:
constructs a lexer, runs tokenization to completion, and returns the resulting
token list. The lexer struct is discarded; only the token list escapes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "php_lex" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex PHP source into a token list

    Let lexer be proc create_php_lexer with source
    Return proc tokenize_php with lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOKEN ACCESSORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Accessor exposing a token's type to callers (parser / Stage B probe) without
exposing the struct layout. Returns EOF for a null token so callers never
dereference 0.
@End Reasoning
Process called "token_get_type" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a token's type tag

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor exposing a token's lexeme (an owned substring copy created at tokenize
time) to callers without exposing the struct layout.
@End Reasoning
Process called "token_get_lexeme" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a token's lexeme (owned copy)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the 1-based source line where the token started, used by the
parser to attach diagnostics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "token_get_line" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a token's source line

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the 1-based source column where the token started, paired with
token_get_line to form a full source coordinate.
@End Reasoning
Process called "token_get_column" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a token's source column

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER HANDLING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bounded character lookahead. Returns 0 at EOF so callers can use 0 as a "no
character" sentinel without a separate at_eof helper.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look at current character without advancing

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    If position is greater than or equal to len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
One-step lookahead used by multi-character operator, comment, and tag
detection. Returns 0 past EOF for the same sentinel-friendly reason.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_next_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look ahead one character

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    Let idx be position plus 1
    If idx is greater than or equal to len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, idx
End Process

@Reasoning:
N-step lookahead used by '<?php' tag detection, '===' / '<=>' / '??=' operator
disambiguation, and heredoc/nowdoc opener scanning that needs more than one
byte ahead.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char_at" takes lexer as Integer, ahead as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look ahead 'ahead' characters from current position

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    Let idx be position plus ahead
    If idx is greater than or equal to len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, idx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one character and updates position plus line/column tracking. Detecting
newline (ASCII 10) here gives every consumer accurate line/column for free.
Returns the consumed character (0 at EOF) so callers can compose it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Move to next character

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position

    If ch is equal to 10:                Note: Newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, column
    End If

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Converts an end-exclusive [start, end) byte span into the (start, length) form
string_substring expects, clamping a negative span to zero so a malformed span
yields an empty lexeme rather than an out-of-range read. The returned substring
is an owned copy so each token holds its own lexeme.
@End Reasoning
Process called "php_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Owned substring over [start_pos, end_pos)

    Let length be end_pos minus start_pos
    If length is less than 0:
        Set length to 0
    End If
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WHITESPACE AND COMMENTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
PHP treats spaces, tabs, CR, and LF as insignificant whitespace (unlike Elixir
there are no newline tokens). '//' and '#' begin line comments; '/*' begins a
block comment. All trivia is skipped inline so the dispatcher never sees it.
'#[' is NOT a comment - it is the PHP 8 attribute opener, so '#' followed by '['
is left for the dispatcher.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and comments

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        If ch is equal to 32:                Note: Space
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 9:             Note: Tab
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 13:        Note: CR
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 10:    Note: LF
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        If ch is equal to 35:    Note: '#'
                            Let after_hash be proc peek_next_char with lexer
                            If after_hash is equal to 91:    Note: '[' attribute opener, not a comment
                                Return 1
                            Otherwise:
                                proc skip_line_comment with lexer
                            End If
                        Otherwise:
                            If ch is equal to 47:    Note: '/'
                                Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
                                If nx is equal to 47:        Note: '//'
                                    proc skip_line_comment with lexer
                                Otherwise:
                                    If nx is equal to 42:    Note: '/*'
                                        proc skip_block_comment with lexer
                                    Otherwise:
                                        Return 1
                                    End If
                                End If
                            Otherwise:
                                Return 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
'//' and '#' line comments run to end of line, but a PHP close tag '?>' inside a
line comment terminates the comment and PHP mode. We stop at LF or at a '?>'
sequence (leaving the '?>' for the dispatcher) so HTML after an inline-closed
comment is handled correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip // or # comment until end of line or ?>

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: consume '/' or '#'
    Let first be proc peek_char with lexer
    If first is equal to 47:             Note: second '/' of '//'
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        If ch is equal to 10:            Note: Newline
            Return 1
        End If
        If ch is equal to 63:            Note: '?'
            Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
            If nx is equal to 62:        Note: '>' close tag ends comment
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
'/* ... */' block comments, including '/** ... */' docblocks. Newlines inside
are consumed via advance_char so line/column tracking outside the comment stays
accurate. Nested block comments are not recognised (PHP, like C, ends at the
first '*/').
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip /* ... */ block comment

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '/'
    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '*'

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        If ch is equal to 42:            Note: '*'
            Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
            If nx is equal to 47:        Note: '/'
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PHP TAG HANDLING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans forward from the current position to find the next PHP open tag without
consuming. Returns 1 if an open tag begins at the current position after
inline-HTML is consumed, 0 if the rest of the source has no open tag. The
inline-HTML body (everything before the tag) is consumed and emitted as a
TOKEN_INLINE_HTML token; on return the cursor sits exactly on the '<' of '<?'.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_open_tag" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume inline HTML up to the next '<?'; return 1 if a tag was found

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Note: No open tag found; leave cursor; caller emits trailing HTML.
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, start
            Return 0
        End If
        If ch is equal to 60:            Note: '<'
            Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
            If nx is equal to 63:        Note: '?'
                Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                If pos is greater than start:
                    Let html be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
                    Let html_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INLINE_HTML, html
                    proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, html_tok
                End If
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits all remaining bytes as a single TOKEN_INLINE_HTML when no further open tag
exists. Used when find_open_tag reports 0 so trailing HTML after the last '?>'
is preserved rather than dropped.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_inline_html_to_end" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit the rest of the file as one inline-HTML token

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    If len is greater than start:
        Let html be proc php_substring with source, start, len
        Let html_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INLINE_HTML, html
        proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, html_tok
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, len
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognises the three PHP open-tag forms and emits the matching token, leaving
the cursor immediately after the tag. '<?php' -> TOKEN_OPEN_TAG; '<?=' ->
TOKEN_OPEN_TAG_ECHO (short echo); '<?' -> TOKEN_OPEN_TAG (short open). The
trailing whitespace after '<?php' is consumed by skip_whitespace on the next
loop iteration, not here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_open_tag" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume a PHP open tag and emit its token

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '<'
    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '?'

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 61:                Note: '=' short-echo tag
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let echo_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_OPEN_TAG_ECHO, "<?="
        proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, echo_tok
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check for 'php'
    Let c0 be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let c1 be proc peek_next_char with lexer
    Let c2 be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 2
    If c0 is equal to 112:               Note: 'p'
        If c1 is equal to 104:           Note: 'h'
            If c2 is equal to 112:       Note: 'p'
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let php_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_OPEN_TAG, "<?php"
                proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, php_tok
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let short_tok be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_OPEN_TAG, "<?"
    proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, short_tok
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOKEN CREATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 40-byte PhpToken and snapshots the lexer's current line/column so
the token records where its first character started. The lexeme is the owned
string the caller already built; value is zeroed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_token" takes lexer as Integer, token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token structure

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, 0

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEXT TOKEN (PHP-mode dispatcher)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The per-token dispatcher uses one character of lookahead to choose a
sub-tokeniser. Order matters: '$' starts a variable; '#[' starts an attribute;
identifier-start chars route to keyword/identifier scanning; digits route to
number scanning; quotes route to string scanning; everything else routes to the
operator/punctuation scanner. Every path consumes at least one byte or returns
EOF/ERROR so the loop always advances.
@End Reasoning
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next PHP-mode token

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF, ""
    End If

    Note: Variable '$name'
    If ch is equal to 36:                Note: '$'
        Return proc scan_variable with lexer
    End If

    Note: Attribute '#['
    If ch is equal to 35:                Note: '#'
        Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
        If nx is equal to 91:            Note: '['
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE_START, "#["
        End If
    End If

    Note: Identifier or keyword
    If proc is_ident_start with ch:
        Return proc scan_identifier with lexer
    End If

    Note: Number literal
    If proc is_digit with ch:
        Return proc scan_number with lexer
    End If

    Note: Double-quoted string (interpolating)
    If ch is equal to 34:                Note: '"'
        Return proc scan_double_string with lexer
    End If

    Note: Single-quoted string (non-interpolating)
    If ch is equal to 39:                Note: "'"
        Return proc scan_single_string with lexer
    End If

    Note: Heredoc / Nowdoc '<<<'
    If ch is equal to 60:                Note: '<'
        Let n1 be proc peek_next_char with lexer
        Let n2 be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 2
        If n1 is equal to 60:
            If n2 is equal to 60:
                Return proc scan_heredoc with lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Operators and punctuation
    Return proc scan_operator with lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: VARIABLE SCANNING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A PHP variable is '$' followed by an identifier. The leading '$' is preserved in
the lexeme (PHP convention) so Stage B can distinguish variables from bare
identifiers without re-prefixing. A lone '$' (variable-variable '$$x' start, or
malformed) still emits a TOKEN_VARIABLE with just '$' so the loop advances; the
parser handles '$$' as a separate case via two TOKEN_VARIABLE/'$' tokens.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_variable" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a $variable

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '$'

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_ident_part with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_VARIABLE, lexeme
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IDENTIFIER AND KEYWORD SCANNING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an identifier run (letters/digits/underscore starting from a non-digit)
then routes the captured text through keyword_type. PHP keywords are
case-insensitive so keyword_type lowercases before comparing. Non-keywords emit
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER with the original-case lexeme preserved.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_ident_part with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
    Let kw be proc keyword_type with lexeme
    Return proc create_token with lexer, kw, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Case-insensitive keyword lookup. Lowercases the input then performs linear
string-equality dispatch across all PHP keywords, language constructs, word
operators, built-in type names, and the three literal constants. Returns the
matched TOKEN_* constant, or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for a user-defined name. Linear
scan is appropriate for an offline translation frontend.
@End Reasoning
Process called "keyword_type" takes word as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map a lexeme to its keyword token type (case-insensitive)

    Let lower be proc string_to_lower with word

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "namespace":
        Return TOKEN_NAMESPACE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "use":
        Return TOKEN_USE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "class":
        Return TOKEN_CLASS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "interface":
        Return TOKEN_INTERFACE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "trait":
        Return TOKEN_TRAIT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "enum":
        Return TOKEN_ENUM
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "function":
        Return TOKEN_FUNCTION
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "const":
        Return TOKEN_CONST
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "extends":
        Return TOKEN_EXTENDS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "implements":
        Return TOKEN_IMPLEMENTS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "insteadof":
        Return TOKEN_INSTEADOF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "public":
        Return TOKEN_PUBLIC
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "private":
        Return TOKEN_PRIVATE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "protected":
        Return TOKEN_PROTECTED
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "static":
        Return TOKEN_STATIC
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "abstract":
        Return TOKEN_ABSTRACT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "final":
        Return TOKEN_FINAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "readonly":
        Return TOKEN_READONLY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "var":
        Return TOKEN_VAR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "global":
        Return TOKEN_GLOBAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "if":
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "elseif":
        Return TOKEN_ELSEIF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "else":
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "while":
        Return TOKEN_WHILE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "do":
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "for":
        Return TOKEN_FOR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "foreach":
        Return TOKEN_FOREACH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "as":
        Return TOKEN_AS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "switch":
        Return TOKEN_SWITCH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "case":
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "default":
        Return TOKEN_DEFAULT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "match":
        Return TOKEN_MATCH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "break":
        Return TOKEN_BREAK
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "continue":
        Return TOKEN_CONTINUE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "return":
        Return TOKEN_RETURN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "goto":
        Return TOKEN_GOTO
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "endif":
        Return TOKEN_ENDIF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "endwhile":
        Return TOKEN_ENDWHILE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "endfor":
        Return TOKEN_ENDFOR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "endforeach":
        Return TOKEN_ENDFOREACH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "endswitch":
        Return TOKEN_ENDSWITCH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "try":
        Return TOKEN_TRY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "catch":
        Return TOKEN_CATCH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "finally":
        Return TOKEN_FINALLY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "throw":
        Return TOKEN_THROW
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "fn":
        Return TOKEN_FN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "yield":
        Return TOKEN_YIELD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "new":
        Return TOKEN_NEW
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "clone":
        Return TOKEN_CLONE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "instanceof":
        Return TOKEN_INSTANCEOF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "and":
        Return TOKEN_AND_WORD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "or":
        Return TOKEN_OR_WORD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "xor":
        Return TOKEN_XOR_WORD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "echo":
        Return TOKEN_ECHO
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "print":
        Return TOKEN_PRINT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "isset":
        Return TOKEN_ISSET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "unset":
        Return TOKEN_UNSET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "empty":
        Return TOKEN_EMPTY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "list":
        Return TOKEN_LIST
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "array":
        Return TOKEN_ARRAY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "declare":
        Return TOKEN_DECLARE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "include":
        Return TOKEN_INCLUDE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "include_once":
        Return TOKEN_INCLUDE_ONCE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "require":
        Return TOKEN_REQUIRE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "require_once":
        Return TOKEN_REQUIRE_ONCE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "exit":
        Return TOKEN_EXIT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "die":
        Return TOKEN_EXIT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "null":
        Return TOKEN_NULL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "true":
        Return TOKEN_TRUE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "false":
        Return TOKEN_FALSE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "int":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_INT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "float":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_FLOAT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "string":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_STRING
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "bool":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_BOOL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "void":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_VOID
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "mixed":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_MIXED
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "object":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_OBJECT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "iterable":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_ITERABLE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "callable":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_CALLABLE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "never":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_NEVER
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "self":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_SELF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower, "parent":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE_PARENT
    End If

    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII-lowercases a string for case-insensitive keyword matching. Builds a fresh
owned result by appending each transformed character; uppercase A..Z (65..90)
map to a..z by adding 32, everything else copies unchanged. PHP identifiers are
ASCII so a byte-level transform is correct.
@End Reasoning
Process called "string_to_lower" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ASCII lowercase a string

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, i
        Let out_ch be ch
        If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
            If ch is less than or equal to 90:
                Set out_ch to ch plus 32
            End If
        End If
        Let piece be proc char_to_string from StringCore with out_ch
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, piece
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMBER SCANNING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
PHP numeric literals: decimal integers and floats, hex (0x), octal (0o or
leading-0), binary (0b), with optional '_' digit separators, optional fractional
part, and optional [eE][+-]? exponent for decimals. We classify the captured
span as int vs float by whether a '.' or exponent appeared. Hex/octal/binary are
always integer tokens. The raw lexeme (with prefix and separators) is preserved
for Stage B which decodes the value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a numeric literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let is_float be 0

    Let first be proc peek_char with lexer
    If first is equal to 48:             Note: '0' - possible hex/octal/binary prefix
        Let nx be proc peek_next_char with lexer
        If nx is equal to 120:           Note: 'x'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_hex_digits with lexer
            Let pos_hex be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lex_hex be proc php_substring with source, start, pos_hex
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lex_hex
        End If
        If nx is equal to 88:            Note: 'X'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_hex_digits with lexer
            Let pos_hex2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lex_hex2 be proc php_substring with source, start, pos_hex2
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lex_hex2
        End If
        If nx is equal to 98:            Note: 'b' binary
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_bin_digits with lexer
            Let pos_bin be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lex_bin be proc php_substring with source, start, pos_bin
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lex_bin
        End If
        If nx is equal to 66:            Note: 'B' binary
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_bin_digits with lexer
            Let pos_bin2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lex_bin2 be proc php_substring with source, start, pos_bin2
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lex_bin2
        End If
        If nx is equal to 111:           Note: 'o' explicit octal
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_dec_digits with lexer
            Let pos_oct be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lex_oct be proc php_substring with source, start, pos_oct
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lex_oct
        End If
        If nx is equal to 79:            Note: 'O' explicit octal
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_dec_digits with lexer
            Let pos_oct2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lex_oct2 be proc php_substring with source, start, pos_oct2
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lex_oct2
        End If
    End If

    Note: Decimal integer part (with '_' separators)
    proc scan_dec_digits with lexer

    Note: Fractional part
    Let dot be proc peek_char with lexer
    If dot is equal to 46:               Note: '.'
        Let after_dot be proc peek_next_char with lexer
        If proc is_digit with after_dot:
            Set is_float to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer    Note: '.'
            proc scan_dec_digits with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Exponent
    Let e be proc peek_char with lexer
    If e is equal to 101:                Note: 'e'
        Set is_float to 1
        proc advance_char with lexer
        proc scan_exponent_sign with lexer
        proc scan_dec_digits with lexer
    Otherwise:
        If e is equal to 69:             Note: 'E'
            Set is_float to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_exponent_sign with lexer
            proc scan_dec_digits with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL, lexeme
    End If
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a run of decimal digits and embedded '_' separators. Shared by the
integer part, fractional part, exponent digits, and explicit-octal digits.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_dec_digits" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume decimal digits and '_' separators

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_digit with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 95:        Note: '_' separator
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a run of hex digits (0-9, a-f, A-F) and '_' separators following a
'0x' prefix.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_hex_digits" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume hex digits and '_' separators

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_hex_digit with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 95:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a run of binary digits ('0' / '1') and '_' separators following a '0b'
prefix.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_bin_digits" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume binary digits and '_' separators

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 48:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 49:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 95:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes an optional '+' or '-' sign immediately after an 'e'/'E' exponent
marker. No-op when the next character is a digit.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_exponent_sign" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume an optional exponent sign

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 43:                Note: '+'
        proc advance_char with lexer
    Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 45:            Note: '-'
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRING SCANNING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-quoted PHP strings do not interpolate and only honour two escapes: \\'
and \\\\. We capture the entire literal including the surrounding quotes so
Stage B receives the exact source slice and applies single-quote unescaping. The
scanner advances past escaped characters so an escaped closing quote does not
terminate the string early. An unterminated string still emits a token so the
loop terminates.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_single_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a single-quoted string literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: opening "'"

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If ch is equal to 92:            Note: '\' escape
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let esc be proc peek_char with lexer
            If esc is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 39:        Note: closing "'"
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Break
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Double-quoted PHP strings interpolate variables ('$x', '{$x->y}', '${name}') and
honour the full escape set. The lexer captures the raw source slice (including
quotes and interpolation markers); variable expansion is performed by Stage B,
not here. We track brace nesting so a closing '}' inside '{$...}' does not end
the string, and we skip escaped characters so '\\"' does not terminate early.
The token type is TOKEN_TEMPLATE_STRING to signal "may contain interpolation".
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_double_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a double-quoted (interpolating) string literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: opening '"'

    Let brace_depth be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If ch is equal to 92:            Note: '\' escape
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let esc be proc peek_char with lexer
            If esc is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 123:       Note: '{' (interpolation block)
                Set brace_depth to brace_depth plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 125:   Note: '}'
                    If brace_depth is greater than 0:
                        Set brace_depth to brace_depth minus 1
                    End If
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 34:    Note: closing '"'
                        If brace_depth is equal to 0:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            Break
                        Otherwise:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_TEMPLATE_STRING, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Heredoc ('<<<LABEL' / '<<<"LABEL"') interpolates like a double-quoted string;
nowdoc ('<<<\\'LABEL\\'') is literal like a single-quoted string. Both end at a
line whose first non-whitespace content is the label. We capture the full
literal from '<<<' through the closing label so Stage B can strip the markers
and (for heredoc) interpolate. We classify by whether the opening label was
single-quoted (nowdoc) or not (heredoc).
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_heredoc" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a heredoc or nowdoc literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '<'
    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '<'
    proc advance_char with lexer        Note: '<'

    Note: Optional whitespace after <<<
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ws be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ws is equal to 32:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ws is equal to 9:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Determine nowdoc vs heredoc by quote style of the label
    Let is_nowdoc be 0
    Let q be proc peek_char with lexer
    If q is equal to 39:                 Note: "'" nowdoc
        Set is_nowdoc to 1
        proc advance_char with lexer
    Otherwise:
        If q is equal to 34:             Note: '"' quoted heredoc
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Capture label characters
    Let label_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let lc be proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_ident_part with lc:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    Let label_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let label be proc php_substring with source, label_start, label_end

    Note: Consume optional closing quote of the opening label
    Let cq be proc peek_char with lexer
    If cq is equal to 39:
        proc advance_char with lexer
    Otherwise:
        If cq is equal to 34:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Consume to end of opening line
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let eol be proc peek_char with lexer
        If eol is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If eol is equal to 10:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Note: Read body lines until a line whose first non-blank token is the label
    proc scan_heredoc_body with lexer, label

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc php_substring with source, start, pos
    If is_nowdoc is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NOWDOC, lexeme
    End If
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_HEREDOC, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans heredoc/nowdoc body lines until it reaches the terminating line. PHP 7.3+
allows the closing label to be indented; the terminator is recognised when, at
line start, optional spaces/tabs are followed by the exact label and then a
non-identifier character (so 'LABELS' does not falsely close 'LABEL'). On match
the label is consumed and scanning stops; the cursor sits just after the label.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_heredoc_body" takes lexer as Integer, label as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume heredoc body until the closing label line

    Let label_len be proc string_length from StringCore with label

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: At the start of a line: skip leading spaces/tabs
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let ws be proc peek_char with lexer
            If ws is equal to 32:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If ws is equal to 9:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End While

        Note: Try to match the label at the current position
        Let matched be proc match_label_here with lexer, label, label_len
        If matched is equal to 1:
            Note: Consume the label characters
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than label_len:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Set k to k plus 1
            End While
            Return 1
        End If

        Note: Not the terminator: consume the rest of this line
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
            If ch is equal to 0:
                Return 1
            End If
            If ch is equal to 10:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End While
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns 1 when the label string appears verbatim at the current cursor and is
followed by a non-identifier character (or end-of-line / EOF / ';'), which is
the PHP rule for a closing heredoc/nowdoc label. Does not advance the cursor;
the caller advances on a match.
@End Reasoning
Process called "match_label_here" takes lexer as Integer, label as Integer, label_len as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Test whether 'label' occurs at the cursor as a closing marker

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than label_len:
        Let want be proc string_char_at from StringCore with label, i
        Let got be proc peek_char_at with lexer, i
        If want is not equal to got:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Character right after the label must not continue an identifier
    Let after be proc peek_char_at with lexer, label_len
    If proc is_ident_part with after:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OPERATOR AND PUNCTUATION SCANNING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single dispatch routine for all PHP operators, delimiters and punctuation, using
longest-match: every multi-character form is checked before its prefixes (e.g.
'===' before '==' before '='; '<=>' before '<='; '<<=' before '<<' before '<';
'??=' before '??'; '?->' before '?'; '**=' before '**' before '*'; '...' before
'.'). Each branch consumes exactly the matched bytes and emits one token, so the
caller always advances. An unrecognised byte is consumed and emitted as
TOKEN_ERROR to guarantee forward progress.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_operator" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan an operator or punctuation token

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let n1 be proc peek_next_char with lexer
    Let n2 be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 2

    Note: '+' '++' '+='
    If ch is equal to 43:
        If n1 is equal to 43:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INC, "++"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS_ASSIGN, "+="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS, "+"
    End If

    Note: '-' '--' '-=' '->'
    If ch is equal to 45:
        If n1 is equal to 45:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_DEC, "--"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS_ASSIGN, "-="
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 62:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW, "->"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS, "-"
    End If

    Note: '*' '**' '**=' '*='
    If ch is equal to 42:
        If n1 is equal to 42:
            If n2 is equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_POW_ASSIGN, "**="
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_POW, "**"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR_ASSIGN, "*="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR, "*"
    End If

    Note: '/' '/=' (comments already handled by skip_whitespace)
    If ch is equal to 47:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH_ASSIGN, "/="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH, "/"
    End If

    Note: '%' '%='
    If ch is equal to 37:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT_ASSIGN, "%="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT, "%"
    End If

    Note: '.' '...' '.='
    If ch is equal to 46:
        If n1 is equal to 46:
            If n2 is equal to 46:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ELLIPSIS, "..."
            End If
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_CONCAT_ASSIGN, ".="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_CONCAT, "."
    End If

    Note: '=' '==' '===' '=>'
    If ch is equal to 61:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            If n2 is equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_IDENTICAL, "==="
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQ, "=="
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 62:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW, "=>"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ASSIGN, "="
    End If

    Note: '!' '!=' '!=='
    If ch is equal to 33:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            If n2 is equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NOT_IDENTICAL, "!=="
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NEQ, "!="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_BANG, "!"
    End If

    Note: '<' '<=' '<=>' '<<' '<<=' '<>'
    If ch is equal to 60:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            If n2 is equal to 62:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SPACESHIP, "<=>"
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LE, "<="
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 60:
            If n2 is equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SHL_ASSIGN, "<<="
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SHL, "<<"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 62:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NEQ, "<>"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LT, "<"
    End If

    Note: '>' '>=' '>>' '>>='
    If ch is equal to 62:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_GE, ">="
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 62:
            If n2 is equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SHR_ASSIGN, ">>="
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SHR, ">>"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_GT, ">"
    End If

    Note: '&' '&&' '&='
    If ch is equal to 38:
        If n1 is equal to 38:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_BOOL_AND, "&&"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_AND_ASSIGN, "&="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_AMP, "&"
    End If

    Note: '|' '||' '|='
    If ch is equal to 124:
        If n1 is equal to 124:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_BOOL_OR, "||"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_OR_ASSIGN, "|="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PIPE, "|"
    End If

    Note: '^' '^='
    If ch is equal to 94:
        If n1 is equal to 61:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_XOR_ASSIGN, "^="
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_CARET, "^"
    End If

    Note: '~'
    If ch is equal to 126:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_TILDE, "~"
    End If

    Note: '?' '??' '??=' '?->'
    If ch is equal to 63:
        If n1 is equal to 63:
            If n2 is equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_COALESCE_ASSIGN, "??="
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_COALESCE, "??"
        End If
        If n1 is equal to 45:
            If n2 is equal to 62:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NULLSAFE_ARROW, "?->"
            End If
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_QUESTION, "?"
    End If

    Note: ':' '::'
    If ch is equal to 58:
        If n1 is equal to 58:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, "::"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_COLON, ":"
    End If

    Note: Single-character delimiters
    If ch is equal to 40:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LPAREN, "("
    End If
    If ch is equal to 41:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RPAREN, ")"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 123:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACE, "{"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 125:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACE, "}"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 91:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACKET, "["
    End If
    If ch is equal to 93:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACKET, "]"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 59:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SEMICOLON, ";"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 44:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_COMMA, ","
    End If
    If ch is equal to 92:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_BACKSLASH, "\\"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 64:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_AT, "@"
    End If

    Note: Unknown byte: consume and flag as error so the loop advances.
    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let bad be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, bad
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER CLASS PREDICATES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start predicate: ASCII letters and underscore. PHP identifiers are
ASCII (with a legacy high-byte extension this frontend does not model).
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_ident_start" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Letter or underscore

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If ch is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-continuation predicate: identifier-start characters plus digits.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_ident_part" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Letter, digit, or underscore

    If proc is_ident_start with ch:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc is_digit with ch:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit predicate (0..9 = bytes 48..57).
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ASCII digit

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex-digit predicate: 0..9, a..f, A..F. Used by hex-literal scanning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Hexadecimal digit

    If proc is_digit with ch:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process
